These instructions are for the AI agent.

Do not Update this file.

As you fulfill prompts, keep these instructions in mind. 

Ensure that the project is well-documented and easy to understand.

Ensure that the project is well-tested and easy to maintain.

Documentation claims should have a minimum of one corresponding test.

Documentaion should be written in a user-friendly style, with attractive Headers, Subheaders, Sub-Sub headers in bold.

Documentation claims and corresponding tests should be cross-referenced. 

Each claim should be followed by the TestIds of the Test(s) associated with it.

No feature will prevent specific keypresses from reaching focused text input controls.  

Claims should be supported in the documentation by references to code filenames, functions, constants, variables, etc.

Ensure that these instructions are followed and that the project is updated accordingly.


core/faceOrientationKeyMapping.ts is a critical file that maps the face orientation to the key mapping.


core/faceOrientationKeyMapping should not be modified without express approval.

It also can be used to determine the orientation of the next dominant face.

Understand that I refer to a "face" I am referring to one of the 24 possible orientations of the cube.

If the Top side is on top, then this means the current angle is zero degrees.

Documentation claims should be in HTML not markdown.

Don't ever remove documentation claims. Mark sections DEPRECATED if you would like to remove them, and include the Date,time, and effective prompt.

Always make sure that all user controls are appropriately documented in a user-friendly style, with each claim  followed by the supporting tests. 

Documentation should be structured in a visually-pleasing manner, with Headings, Subheadings,  and labels bolded.

For deprecated claims, explain clearly why they are deprecated if they are not already deprecated.

Ensure that each claim has a unique ID.  This unique ID should be displayed as a link in the TestingPanel before the test item  

Clicking the claim link should pop up a hint displaying the content of the corresponding documentation claim. 

Tests panel components should align horizontally.

Tests panel items should include explanatory text so the tester knows exactly what to do.

